widespread social and political transformation. Resonant Violence explores both the enduring impacts of genocidal violence and the varied ways in which states and grassroots collectives respond to and transform this violence through memory practices and grassroots activism. By calling upon lessons from Germany, Poland, Argentina, and the Indigenous United States, Resonant Violence demonstrates how ordinary individuals come together to engage with a violent past to pave the way for a less violent future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCollective memory. 0aGenocidexPolitical aspects. 0aGenocidexSocial aspects. 0aViolence. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  agenocide, political violence, human right, human rights, memory, actiivist, activism, Argentina, Holocaust, Germany, merican Indian populations, American Indian, Cambodia, mass killing, Native American, twenty-first century, violence, economic disparity, inequality, institutional discrimination, Alcatraz Island, Alcatraz, grassroots activism, Poland, grassroot.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076647940uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197882559840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978825598423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978825598/original  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK